The paper discusses techniques for similarity search and estimation in high-dimensional spaces, which are common problems in computer science. The use of locality-sensitive hashing (LSH) is a fundamental technique for solving these problems, which suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.DB (Databases) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper focuses on point sets and polygons, which are geometric objects, indicating that it could also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of consistent sampling, which is a technique commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and information retrieval (cs.IR), suggesting that it could belong to these sub-categories as well. Overall, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS and cs.CG, followed by cs.CV, cs.DB, and cs.IR.
